<font color="#FF0000">THINKING OUT LOUD, AGAIN...</font><br>
<tt>Wed Aug 20 20:30:30 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Gerald, you make some good points, because the perceived enemy is, in fact, the enemy, by any name. However, names are meaningless in the face of life in the extreme.<br><br>
I don't mean to get fancy, but life in the extreme, and survival, evokes the dehumanized architype human in us all, that baseline or core instinctual animal whose only drive is to survive, and for whom all rules mean nothing. Killing does this to people.<br><br>
This is not a bad thing in the context in which we found it in ourselves, and certainly nothing to evoke shame or guilt. It is in the aftermath when those in whom we placed our trust did not care enough or know enough to bring many of us back into society in a way that made these extreme architype things the bad memories they really ought to be. Many of those same people now criticize for those things that just got stuck in our heads through no fault of our own. <br><br>
Many societies, ancient and &quot;new&quot;, have recognized this problem and have done, and do, those things which realign their soldiers, warriors, or whatever they are called, to be reestablished as stable constructive citizens. <br><br>
As Ed so aptly put it, calling the enemy a name to keep one's sanity, is not a crime. I know I did. There were times that it kept my sanity. I do not do it now unless I am triggered, an unfortunate circumstance I fight continually to control. I don't even think &quot;barbaric&quot; is appropriate. I reserve that for those who willfully and with full cognition go beyond for no good reason.<br><br>
Sure, I engaged and killed the ememy with the means for which I was trained. I may have had a long reach, but the blood heat of killing is very much the same for most when you crash and burn in the midst of it all.<br><br>
Clearly, how each of us deals with these things is very much an individual process. Cook has his way, Ed his, and I have mine. Although we may not even agree at times, it is the process that is the most important, to be understood, and eventually respected.<br><br>
So, Cook, if &quot;commies&quot; are part of your way of looking at things, you will get no argument from me!
